Four organisations admitted as friends of the court have been granted permission to present oral arguments to the court. CAPE TOWN - The Constitutional Court will hear the United Democratic Movement s (UDM) case for a secret ballot in a vote of no confidence in President Jacob Zuma on 15 May.The Chief Justice has issued further directives that all parties will have to comply with before that date.A debate on a motion of no confidence in the president was scheduled for last month, but it was postponed by the speaker of the National Assembly on the request of opposition parties, to await the outcome of the court application.Speaker Baleka Mbete agreed to reconvene Parliament during the recess last month, to hold a debate on a motion of no confidence in President Zuma at the request of opposition parties.But after she said it was not within her rights to allow a secret ballot, the UDM approached the Constitutional Court last month.The Chief Justice has now ordered the UDM to file its final papers by Monday.Four organisations admitted as friends of the court have been granted permission to present oral arguments to the court.The Speaker and the Presidency may file written responses to submissions by these organisations by next Friday.(Edited by Winnie Thelestane)